letion handling currently re-reads `oursDoc` after the merge has been applied. If a document was updated by the merge, then `oursDoc.content` is no longer the pre-merge content. But the check `valuesEqual(baseContent, oursContent)` is meant to check whether we modified the document — if we did, it's a conflict (which was already handled), and if we didn't, accept the deletion.\n\nThe issue is: after applying the merge, `oursDoc.content` may have been updated. But for the deletion case, the merge wouldn't have updated the document (since `theirsContent === null` and we skip those cases in the main loop). So actually, the document won't be in the `merged` map, and the merge application won't touch it. The re-read is fine because the document wasn't modified by the merge application step.\n\nWait, let me trace through more carefully. In the main loop, when `baseContent !== null && theirsContent === null && oursContent !== null`:\n- If `!valuesEqual(baseContent, oursContent)` — it's a conflict, we don't apply\n- If `valuesEqual(baseContent, oursContent)` — we `continue` without adding to merged\n\nThen in the deletion handling after merge application, we check the same condition and delete if ours equals base. But in the `continue` case, `oursDoc.content` hasn't been touched by the merge (since it's not in `merged`), so the re-check is safe. Good.\n\nBut there's actually a more subtle bug: the deletion handling loop runs over `allDocIds` but after the merge has been applied, some documents may have been modified. However, for the `baseContent !== null && theirsContent === null` case, the document wasn't touched by merge application. So it's safe.\n\nLet me now write a quick sanity test to be sure."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":116,"cache_read_input_tokens":46779,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":116},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"